step.tex:
\begin{align}

I &= \int \dfrac{3 \sin (2 x+1) - \sin (6x +3)}{4} dx \\
&= \dfrac{3}{4} \int sin(2x+1) dx - \dfrac{1}{4}\int  \sin(6x+3) dx \\
&= \dfrac{-3}{8}\cos (2x + 1) + \dfrac{1}{24} \cos (6 x + 3) + C
\end{align}

\begin{align}

I &= \int \dfrac{3 \sin (2 x+1) - \sin (6x +3)}{4} dx \\
&= \dfrac{3}{4} \int sin(2x+1) dx - \dfrac{1}{4}\int  \sin(6x+3) dx \\
&= \dfrac{3}{8}\cos (2x + 1) - \dfrac{1}{24} \cos (6 x + 3) + C
\end{align}

step.reason:
\int \sin (a x)dx =  \dfrac{- \cos (a x)}{a}+ C_1 \\
\text{Alternatively, proceed with }
\sin^3 x = \sin^2 x \cdot \sin x  \\
\text{which gives } 
\dfrac{-1}{2} \cos (2x +1) + \dfrac{1}{6} \cos^3 (2x+1) + C \\
\text{Both answers are equivalent.}
